topic.title: Electrical Specifications

body.p: The following section describes the electrical specifications of the HB20 device. Unless stated otherwise, the operating conditions are VBATT equal to 1.2 V, VDDIO equal to 1.8 V, 25 °C and non-buck mode. Please note that extended time at absolute maximum supply may reduce the life of the device.

li.p: Supply rise time is defined as the time to reach 95% of the final supply voltage.
Processor ready time is defined as the time from application of VBATT until the processor is ready to receive commands or start running an application.
An allowance is made for the VDDIO voltage to lag the VBATT voltage by up to 25 ms. Please note that there is no restriction on the VDDIO voltage settling faster than the VBATT voltage.

li.p: The TX power range may be extended down to –30 dBm but with larger steps of output power control.

The harmonics are based on an internal, factory-calibrated matching network that is optimized for output power. An additional external harmonic filter can be used as shown in figure HB_WS Buck Mode Implementation to reduce the second harmonic by at least 10 dB and the third harmonic by at least 30 dB. A small increase in TX current consumption of 300 µA (non-buck mode) may result from using an additional external filter but with no additional output power loss. Please note that the harmonic levels in this table are with reference to using a continuous wave TX signal. A reduction of 2 dB and 4.5 dB (second and third harmonics, respectively) can be considered when using a modulated TX signal.
The second harmonic is minimized in the factory using an on-chip calibration.
The fourth and fifth harmonics are lower than –50 dBm.
The RF-PHY TX complies with all other mandated Bluetooth characteristics as per the RF-PHY test specification (TS.5.1). Please note that stable modulation is not supported.

body.p: ADC2 may be configured as a general-purpose ADC supporting both incremental and continuous modes of operation. Incremental mode should be used when quick measurements are required as for measuring the temperature and battery voltage. The ADC clock source of 32 MHz is used for the general-purpose ADC. Please note that the external capacitor C4 is not required to operate the general-purpose ADC.

entry.p: Single-ended input voltage range around common mode

li.p: Incremental mode is used for making single ADC measurements and sampling multiple channels with the ADC controller. If six channels are sampled in series, then the maximum effective sample rate of each channel is 1.26 kbps.
The input voltage range is defined as the range of inputs where the gain compression at the output of the ADC is < 10 mV.
The common mode voltage is supplied by the HB20 device.

Dynamic range is calculated as the ratio of the highest usable RMS signal level to the input referred noise. The maximum dynamic range is measured with a single-ended input voltage of 300 mV. Measured when sampling one channel in incremental mode with Fs equal to 3.8 ksps and Vin-sepk equal to 300 mV. Please note that the dynamic range may reduce to 66 dB when multiple channels are sampled back to back.
The input referred noise is measured on one channel with Fs equal to 3.8 ksps.
Precision is defined as the standard deviation of repeated measurements at one temperature or battery voltage.

Battery accuracy is defined as the maximum error between the actual and measured battery voltage over the specified range. The accuracy specification applies to an operational temperature range of up to 55 °C and the use of AC connected analog IO or floating analog IO.
Battery measurement range 1.8 V to 3.3 V is only available with WS devices.

Temperature accuracy is defined as the maximum error between the actual and measured temperature over the specified range. The accuracy specification applies up to an operational temperature range of between -40 to 55 °C and the use of AC connected analog IO or floating analog IO.

body.p: All three ADCs may be configured as high-fidelity ADCs in continuous mode operation. The ADC clock source of 49.15 MHz (provided by internal audio PLL) needs to be used to generate the internal audio sample rates between 16 ksps and 48 ksps. Alternatively, the 32 MHz reference clock may be used to generate sample rates between 10.4 ksps and 41.6 ksps. The high-fidelity ADCs require the addition of the external capacitor C4 to filter the internally generated reference voltage. Note that the dynamic range of the ADCs may be extended using software control of the preamplifier gain, and the analog IO must be AC-coupled or left floating to meet the following specifications.

body.p: The audio PLL provides the clock source for the high-fidelity ADCs and I2S. The PLL frequency can be programmed dynamically to phase track received audio samples.

entry.p: Output clock period jitter measured on I2S master clock
Current consumption with output frequency = 32.256 MHz
Current consumption with output frequency = 49.152 MHz

li.p: The frequency is controlled by a 20-bit control word according to the following equation: audio PLL frequency = 32 × 106 × (1 + aupllPllDiv[19:0] / 220).
The lowest trim range occurs when the output frequency is set to 32.256 MHz, and the lowest frequency that can be trimmed to is 32 MHz (–7900 ppm away).

body.p: The 32 MHz crystal oscillator has been designed for fast startup. The load capacitors are internal to the HB20 device and are factory-calibrated to give a load capacitance close to 6 pF when using the HB20 reference circuit layout. Customer calibration of the crystal oscillator can also be made to finely adjust the frequency.

table.title: 32 MHz Crystal Oscillator Operating Conditions and Characteristics

li.p: The internal load capacitance is calibrated in the factory. Further calibration may be required depending on the board parasitics.
Additional external capacitance is needed on each pin to meet the crystal load requirements.
The accuracy is defined as the maximum error between the actual frequency and the measured frequency. The RCO is automatically adjusted on every advertising/connection event.

body.p: The 32.768 kHz crystal oscillator may be used instead of the internal RC oscillator for running the wake-up timer in system deep-sleep and sleep modes. Unlike the 32 MHz crystal oscillator, the 32.768 kHz crystal oscillator does not have internal capacitors that can be programmed to adjust the frequency. For this reason, external capacitors are required to set the correct load conditions on the crystal.

table.title: 32.768 kHz Crystal Oscillator Operating Conditions and Characteristics

li.p: Additional external capacitance is needed on each pin to meet the crystal load requirements.
The accuracy is defined as the maximum error between the actual frequency and the measured frequency. The RCO is automatically adjusted on every advertising/connection event.

body.p: The internal RC oscillator may be used by the HB20 device to accurately define advertising and connection events. A continuous auto-calibration system ensures that the frequency accuracy does not exceed the mandated Bluetooth frequency accuracy of ±500 ppm. For the contribution of the RC oscillator to the deep-sleep current consumption, see System Deep Sleep Mode Current Consumption.

li.p: The accuracy is defined as the maximum error between the actual frequency and the measured frequency. The RCO is automatically adjusted on every advertising/connection event.
